event.title: drowned in a canoe on Beaver Dam Lake in 1895

data.event: He continued to live in the area even after it was settled by European settlers and drowned in a canoe on Beaver Dam Lake in 1895.

event.title: 1874, A. Ritan and R. H. Clothier explored

data.event: In 1874, A. Ritan and R. H. Clothier explored the area with the intention of settling in there.

A. Ritan, who lived near what is today Turtle Lake and the Dahlby Family, originally of Norwegian descent, from the town of New Richmond, both filed a homestead near the proposed railroad and built two log cabins, 300 feet north of the present high school location.

event.title: 1878, the North Wisconsin Railroad Company extended

data.event: In 1878, the North Wisconsin Railroad Company extended the rail lines through the area.
In 1880, the Dahlby Family sold their cabin and moved to Chandler (now known as Spooner) and open a store.

event.title: lived in Cumberland for many years

data.event: A. Ritan, also originally from Norway, lived in Cumberland for many years and helped develop the city before moving to Portland, Oregon.
